\textbf{Heads} &
\textbf{($L_p$)} &
\textbf{($L_r$)} &
\textbf{($L_c$)} &
\textbf{Train} &
\\
\midrule
Cognexis-8B     & 4096  & 32  & 8  & 1 & 8  & 12 & $\sim$8B \\
Cognexis-64B    & 8192  & 64  & 10 & 1 & 10 & 16 & $\sim$64B \\
Cognexis-256B   & 12288 & 96  & 12 & 1 & 12 & 20 & $\sim$256B \\
Cognexis-1.28T  & 16384 & 128 & 16 & 1 & 16 & 24 & $\sim$1.28T \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Note that effective depth at inference varies by loop count [1]. For example, Cognexis-8B with 12 loops has an effective depth of $8 + 12 + 8 = 28$ block applications, comparable to a conventional 28-layer transformer [1]. At 1 loop, the same model has an effective depth of only 17 -- a significantly lighter computation that may suffice for simple predictions [1].

\section{Evaluation Framework}

\subsection{Conventional Metrics}

Evaluation follows standard language modeling practice to ensure comparability with non-recurrent baselines [1]. Relevant metrics include perplexity, negative log-likelihood, exact match accuracy, multiple-choice accuracy, Pass@k for code generation, BLEU and ROUGE for generation quality, and human preference judgments for open-ended tasks [1].

For compute-adaptive models, reporting must include complete experimental context [1]. Each result should specify the dataset split, prompt format, decoding configuration (e.g., temperature, top-$p$), loop mode (fixed or adaptive, including iteration counts), and random seed [1]. Without this information, results cannot be reliably reproduced or meaningfully compared [1].

\subsection{Depth Efficiency Index (DEI)}

The Depth Efficiency Index measures how much performance improvement each additional unit of compute buys [1]. It is defined as:

\begin{equation}
\text{DEI}(N) = \frac{M(N) - M(N_0)}{C(N) - C(N_0)}
\end{equation}

where $M(N)$ is a performance metric (e.g., accuracy) at loop count $N$, $M(N_0)$ is the baseline performance at a reference loop count $N_0$ (typically 1), and $C(N)$ is the compute cost in FLOPs at loop count $N$ [1]. In plain terms, DEI answers the question: ``For each additional FLOP I spend on recurrence, how much better does my model get?'' [1]. A high DEI indicates that extra loops are producing good returns; a low DEI suggests diminishing returns [1]. Plotting DEI as a function of $N$ typically reveals a curve that peaks early and declines, providing a clear visual indicator of where the sweet spot lies for a given task [1].

\subsection{Loop Saturation Point (LSP)}

The Loop Saturation Point identifies the most efficient reasoning depth [1]. It is defined as the loop count that maximizes DEI:

\begin{equation}
\text{LSP} = \underset{N}{\text{argmax}} \; \text{DEI}(N)
\end{equation}

At the LSP, the model is getting the best return per unit of additional computation [1]. Beyond the LSP, each additional loop still helps (performance may still improve), but the rate of improvement per FLOP is declining [1]. Inference schedulers can use the LSP as a default loop budget: it represents the depth at which the model is operating most efficiently [1]. Importantly, LSP should be reported per task and per dataset, since different problems saturate at different depths [1]. A math reasoning benchmark may have an LSP of 10, while a simple text completion task may saturate at 2 or 3 [1].

\subsection{Overthinking Threshold (OT)}

The Overthinking Threshold captures the point where additional computation actively hurts performance [1]:

\begin{equation}
\text{OT} = \min\{N : M(N + 1) < M(N)\}
\end{equation}

This is the smallest loop count at which the model's performance begins to decline with further iterations [1]. Overthinking occurs when extra iterations introduce noise, destabilize the hidden state, or cause the model to second-guess correct predictions [1]. It is a real and observed phenomenon in recurrent-depth models -- the model can ``think too much'' and arrive at a worse answer than it had after fewer loops [1]. The adaptive scheduler should be configured to avoid exceeding OT [1]. Because OT is sensitive to individual inputs, it should be reported with confidence intervals across evaluation datasets [1].

\subsection{Depth Gain Ratio (DGR)}

The Depth Gain Ratio provides a simple summary of how much recurrence helps overall [1]:

\begin{equation}
\text{DGR} = \frac{M(N_{\text{max}}) - M(N_0)}{M(N_0)}
\end{equation}

DGR compares the best performance achievable with full recurrence against a no-recurrence baseline [1]. A DGR of 0.15, for example, means that full recurrence improves performance by 15\% over a single-pass baseline [1]. Higher DGR indicates that the recurrent architecture is providing substantial value and that the recurrence mechanism is not merely cosmetic [1]. DGR is most informative when compared across tasks: tasks with high DGR are the ones where compute-adaptive scheduling matters most [1].

\subsection{Scheduler Metrics}

For adaptive scheduling modes, additional metrics are needed to assess the quality of the scheduling decisions themselves [1]. Key scheduler metrics include: average loops used, loop distribution histogram, halt reason distribution, quality at adaptive loops vs. same average fixed loop count, false-halt rate, false-continue rate, scheduler overhead, and budget violation count [1].

A critical evaluation principle: adaptive results must always be compared with fixed-depth baselines at equal total compute [1]. If the adaptive scheduler uses an average of 6 loops, its performance should be compared against a fixed-6-loop baseline [1]. Any performance difference is attributable to the scheduler's ability to allocate loops non-uniformly -- some inputs getting more, others getting less -- rather than simply using more total computation [1].

\section{Safety and Operational Considerations}

The recurrent-depth design introduces a set of safety and operational considerations that are not present in conventional transformer architectures [1]. A primary concern is stability under iteration: excessive loop counts can lead to uncontrolled growth in hidden-state norms, convergence to degenerate fixed points, or oscillatory dynamics that produce unpredictable outputs [1]. Enforcing strict upper bounds on iteration count, along with continuous monitoring of activation magnitudes, is therefore a necessary architectural constraint [1]. Deployment systems require explicit safeguards that terminate recurrence if predefined stability thresholds are exceeded [1].

Adaptive scheduling further introduces the risk of unbounded resource consumption [1]. Certain inputs -- whether adversarially constructed or inherently complex -- may trigger excessive iteration, resulting in significantly higher computational cost than fixed-depth models [1]. To mitigate this, inference must be governed by explicit per-request compute budgets that cap total resource usage irrespective of scheduler decisions [1]. Without such constraints, the system remains vulnerable to denial-of-service scenarios that exploit its adaptive behavior [1].

Variability in iteration count also leads to variability in latency, which may expose timing side channels [1]. In contexts where this is a concern, controlled randomization of loop counts around the scheduler's recommendation can reduce information leakage [1].

Safety mechanisms, including content filtering and refusal policies, must remain invariant across all loop configurations [1]. No choice of iteration count should weaken or bypass these safeguards [1]. Ensuring this requires systematic evaluation across the full range of depths, as safety behavior does not vary monotonically with additional computation [1]. In some cases, increased iteration may improve the model's ability to identify and refuse unsafe requests; in others, it may amplify undesirable outputs [1]. Any loop regimes that degrade safety performance must be identified and restricted within the scheduler's allowable range [1].

\section{Limitations and Future Work}

The Cognexis architecture inherits several limitations from the broader class of recurrent-depth models, alongside challenges specific to its design [1]. The most prominent concern is stability at high iteration counts [1]. Even with gating mechanisms, input injection, spectral normalization, and residual scaling, repeated transformation of hidden states remains inherently sensitive [1]. At sufficiently large loop counts, the system may exhibit divergent behavior, converge to uninformative fixed points, oscillate between attractors, or become overconfident in incorrect predictions [1]. These stabilization techniques are necessary but not universally sufficient, particularly across diverse inputs and scales [1]. Approaches based on contractive transformations or implicit fixed-point methods offer a potential path toward more robust behavior [1].

Training complexity is also significantly increased relative to standard decoder-only models [1]. The introduction of loop curricula, management of gradients across repeated iterations, and the need for stability monitoring expand both implementation complexity and the hyperparameter space [1]. Simpler training strategies that achieve robustness across depths without multi-phase curricula remain an open objective [1]. In parallel, adaptive scheduling introduces variability in inference latency, which complicates deployment in systems with strict service-level constraints [1]. Mechanisms that incorporate deadline awareness and allow controlled degradation of output quality may be required for practical use [1].

Additional open problems arise in several areas [1]. The generalization behavior of learned schedulers remains uncertain, particularly under distribution shift; miscalibration can lead to premature halting or excessive computation [1]. More robust approaches may involve uncertainty-aware estimation or domain-adaptive recalibration [1]. The semantics of KV caching in the presence of recurrent updates are also more complex than in standard transformers, and incorrect reuse can introduce silent errors without explicit failure signals [1]. Extensions to multimodal settings raise further questions about how iterative computation should be distributed across heterogeneous inputs [1]. Integration with external tools introduces another layer of complexity, as scheduling must account for both internal iteration and external calls [1].

Finally, practical deployment requires consideration of hardware variability [1]. The optimal allocation of iterations depends not only on input characteristics but also on system-level factors such as compute throughput, memory bandwidth, and scheduling overhead [1]. Incorporating hardware-aware cost models into the scheduling process represents a natural direction for improving efficiency in real-world environments [1].

\section{Conclusion}

Cognexis reframes scaling in language models by separating reasoning depth from parameter count [1]. By reusing a shared recurrent transformer block, the architecture enables deeper effective computation -- functionally comparable to much deeper networks -- without increasing parameter storage or memory footprint [1]. The inclusion of a compute-adaptive interface, driven by an adaptive loop scheduler and a learned value head, allows inference-time allocation of computation to vary with input difficulty, assigning additional iterations where beneficial and terminating early when sufficient confidence is reached [1]. In this formulation, reasoning depth becomes a controllable runtime variable rather than a fixed architectural property [1].

The specification encompasses the full modeling stack, including tokenization, rotary positional encoding, the three-stage Prelude--Recurrent--Coda structure, stability mechanisms such as gating and input injection, and a multi-mode adaptive scheduling system [1]. It also defines a set of evaluation metrics tailored to iterative computation and provides reference configurations spanning several orders of magnitude in scale [1]. The level of detail is intended to support direct implementation, rather than serving as a high-level conceptual outline [1].

This perspective suggests a shift in how model capability is framed [1]. Rather than focusing solely on parameter count as the primary axis of improvement, attention moves toward how computation is allocated during inference [1]. If the amount of reasoning required varies across inputs, then architectures capable of adapting their depth accordingly offer both efficiency and potential gains in capability [1].

